faq:
  - q: "How much mulch do I need?"
    a: "Multiply the length and width of the bed to get square feet, then multiply by your desired depth in feet. This calculator does that conversion for you and shows cubic feet, cubic yards, bags, and estimated cost."
  - q: "How deep should mulch be?"
    a: "Most landscape beds use 2 to 3 inches of mulch. A 2-inch layer is usually enough for refreshing an existing bed, while 3 inches may be better for new beds or stronger weed suppression."
  - q: "How many cubic feet are in a cubic yard of mulch?"
    a: "There are 27 cubic feet in one cubic yard. Bulk mulch is usually sold by the cubic yard, while bagged mulch is commonly sold in cubic-foot bags."
  - q: "How many 2 cubic foot bags are in a cubic yard?"
    a: "One cubic yard equals 27 cubic feet, so it takes 13.5 two-cubic-foot bags to equal one cubic yard. Since you cannot buy half a bag, round up when planning."
  - q: "Is bagged mulch or bulk mulch better?"
    a: "Bagged mulch is convenient for small projects and easier to transport. Bulk mulch is often more practical for large landscape beds or projects requiring multiple cubic yards."
  - q: "Should I remove old mulch before adding new mulch?"
    a: "You usually do not need to remove all old mulch unless it is matted, moldy, too deep, or mixed with debris. Loosen compacted mulch before adding a fresh layer."
  - q: "Can too much mulch hurt plants?"
    a: "Yes. Mulch that is too deep can hold excess moisture, reduce airflow, and contribute to plant or tree problems. Avoid piling mulch against stems, trunks, or foundations."
  - q: "How often should mulch be replaced?"
    a: "Many homeowners refresh mulch once a year, but timing depends on mulch type, weather, fading, decomposition, and how the bed looks."
  - q: "Should mulch touch tree trunks?"
    a: "No. Keep mulch pulled back from tree trunks and plant stems. A volcano-shaped pile of mulch around a tree can trap moisture and cause problems."
  - q: "Should I add extra mulch to my estimate?"
    a: "A small buffer can help if your beds are uneven or your measurements are rough, but avoid buying so much that the final layer becomes too deep."
